BRUNO'S
WEEKLY

Standing
as
he
does,
the
clear-eyed
patriot
looks
out
and

over
the
busy
highway
of
traffic,
and
at
his
right
hand
rise

the
massive
homes
of
the
daily
press.

When
the
summer
leafage
softens
the
background;
when

the
bare
branches
intensify
the
outlines
of
the
bronze;
when

the
morning
sun
lights
up
the
east
and
spreads
an
aureole

of
glory
behind
his
head;
when
the
sunset's
lingering
rays

touch
that
calm
young
face
with
a
kiss
of
infinite
tender

ness;
when
the
cold
moonlight
wraps
him
in
the
mantle

of
her
shimmering
glory,
always,
always
he
stands
there,

with
fettered
hands
and
feet,
but
with
a
dauntless
spirit

which
no
human
power
can
quell,
which
bows
but
to
the

mandates
of
truth
and
honor.

Yet,
when
the
rush
and
the
turmoil
of
the
week
are
ended

and
over
the
Sabbath
stillness,
the
noontide
chimes
of

Trinity
are
heard,
he
seems
to
assume
more
majestic
pro

portions;
he
stands
a
giant,
fettered
for
his
country's
sake,

and
in
the
voices
of
the
chapel
bells
he
seems
to
hear
the

music
of
the
angels
singing,
and
the
Master's
words,
"Well
done."
